included.description: Upon further investigation into the decision making process we found that users would go through two types of decisions -- important and unimportant. For example, If 6 friends are arguing about where to to eat, they want to just make a decision with no regard to what it is; while a decision deemed important by a group would need more democracy involved. We happened upon integrating both of these decision making types into our device by adding a voting and randomness mode for those who deeply care about the decision at hand or not.
included.title: Transition Diagram

included.description: In this example, I had an idea to create a physical device to aid indecision groups of people encounter. I got this insight from watching my friends argue over how to play Settlers of Catan, and instead of just voting for who was right or wrong to proceed with the game, they just continued to argue. So after deciding on this decision aiding device my group and I went out and did interviews and field observations. We took all the information we gained and completed an affinity diagram.
included.title: Affinity Diagram

included.description: In this example my group and I developed personas for aggressive and passive people who would use a decision making device. We found majority of group indecision occurs from a conflict between passive and aggressive personalities.
